alysis to quantify fractal-like, long-        corporate nonlinear chaos theory to state space models (SSMs)\n17\t                                         range temporal chaotic correlation. CS-ETS surpasses prior            with a significant reduction in the parameter count. We in-\n18\tarXiv:2607.18629v1 [cs.SD] 21 Jul 2026\n19\t\n20\t\n21\t\n22\t\n23\t                                         work with a 40.79% lower parameter count (32M vs 54.1M)               troduce two chaos-inspired losses: LER, which penalizes mis-\n24\t                                         and introduces a new Post-Vocoder Alignment approach that             matches in local divergence rates by aligning Lyapunov Expo-\n25\t                                         improves LSD by 2.1x, STOI by 4.7x, and SI-SDR by 1.25x.              nents across different resolutions; and MSDFA, which exploits\n26\t                                         CS-ETS reduces computation by 13.33% while maintaining im-            detrended fluctuation analysis to quantify fractal-like, long-\n27\t                                         proved performance. To the best of our knowledge, for the first       range temporal chaotic correlation. Our contributions include:\n28\t                                         time, we show how ETS can be supervised by the subtle non-            (1) We introduce “modified Samba-based SSMs” with sliding\n29\t                                         linear chaotic physics with Samba attention to achieve a signif-      window attention, resulting in a 50.1% reduction in encoder\n30\t                                         icantly smaller model with superior performance.                      parameters compared to [5]. (2) We introduce post-vocoder\n31\t                                         Index Terms: Electromyography, Speech Synthesis, Chaos-               alignment, enabling comprehensive acoustic evaluation (LSD,\n32\t                                         Inspired Non