gn\n44\t                                         ministic chaos due to (i) non-stationary motor unit firing pat-\n45\t                                                                                                               Why we design chaos-inspired models: Speech production\n46\t                                         terns varying with force, fatigue, and phonetic context [6, 7],\n47\t                                                                                                               is fundamentally a non-linear dynamical process characterized\n48\t                                         and (ii) temporal summation of asynchronous motor unit action\n49\t                                                                                                               by deterministic chaos [14–16]. Therefore, ETS synthesis is\n50\t                                         potentials creating amplitude modulation and quasi-periodic\n51\t                                                                                                               inherently chaotic because it attempts to reconstruct a funda-\n52\t                                         bursts [8]. Two critical chaotic features, such as (i) recurrent\n53\t                                                                                                               mentally non-linear, feedback-driven speech production system\n54\t                                         activation patterns across phonetic contexts reflecting articula-\n55\t                                                                                                               from partial muscular observations. Small variations in EMG\n56\t                                         tory gestures [9], and (ii) rapid state transitions during coar-\n57\t                                                                                                               signals can therefore produce disproportionately large acoustic\n58\t                                         ticulation [10], can be estimated through Detrended Fluctua-\n59\t                                                                                                               changes, a hallmark of deterministic chaos. Non-chaotic mod-\n60\t                                         tion Analysis [11] and Lyapunov Exponents [12]. These multi-\n61\t                                                                                                               els smooth out these effects, eliminating jitter, turbulence, and\n62\t                                         scale temporal dependencies encode subtle articulatory transi-\n63\t                                                                                                               aperiodic bursts and yielding unnaturally clean speech. Accu-\n64\t                                         tions, co-activation patterns, and speaker-specific muscle coor-\n65\t                                                                                                               rate EMG-to-speech synthesis thus requires non-linear chaos-\n66\t                                         dination essential for accurate phonetic decoding in EMG-to-\n67\t                                                                                                               inspired models that can represent both structured harmonic\n68\t                                         Speech (ETS) conversion [4, 5].\n69\t                                                                                                               content and chaotic, irregular dynamics.\n70\t                                              What current ETS systems miss: Prior works [4, 5, 13]\n71\t                                                                                                                    CS-ETS has the following contributions in its architecture:\n72\t                                  