ov exponents to capture nonlinear fluc-              To the best of our knowledge, our proposed Chaos-inspired\n                                         tuations and sensitivity to initial conditions. MSDFA exploits        Samba-based ETS (CS-ETS) is the first model to explicitly in-\n                                         detrended fluctuation analysis to quantify fractal-like, long-        corporate nonlinear chaos theory to state space models (SSMs)\n                                         range temporal chaotic correlation. CS-ETS surpasses prior            with a significant reduction in the parameter count. We in-\narXiv:2607.18629v1 [cs.SD] 21 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                         work with a 40.79% lower parameter count (32M vs 54.1M)               troduce two chaos-inspired losses: LER, which penalizes mis-\n                                         and introduces a new Post-Vocoder Alignment approach that             matches in local divergence rates by aligning Lyapunov Expo-\n                                         improves LSD by 2.1x, STOI by 4.7x, and SI-SDR by 1.25x.              nents across different resolutions; and MSDFA, which exploits\n                                         CS-ETS reduces computation by 13.33% while maintaining im-            detrended fluctuation analysis to quantify fractal-like, long-\n                                         proved performance. To the best of our knowledge, for the first       range temporal chaotic correlation. Our contributions include:\n                                         time, we show how ETS can be supervised by the subtle non-            (1) We introduce “modified Samba-based SSMs” with sliding\n                                         linear chaotic physics with Samba attention to achieve a signif-      window attention, resulting in a 50.1% reduction in encoder\n                                         icantly smaller model with superior performance.                      parameters compared to [5]. (2) We introduce post-vocoder\n                                         Index Terms: Electromyography, Speech Synthesis, Chaos-               alignment, enabling comprehensive acoustic evaluation (LSD,\n                                         Inspired Nonlinear Dynamics, State-space Models                       STOI, PESQ, SISDR, NISQA-MOS, see Section 3.3 for full\n                                                                                                               form) beyond WER for the first time in ETS. CS-ETS delivers\n                                                              1. Introduction                                  the 2.1x best spectral reconstruction (LSD = 1.07 vs 2.25), 4.7x\n                                         Silent speech interfaces (SSIs) allow speech synthesis without        improvement in intelligibility (STOI = 0.61 vs 0.13), and 1.25x\n                                         vocalization by interpreting articulatory bio-signals [1], sup-       improvement in noise reduction (SI-SDR = -33.41 vs -41.96)\n                                         porting individuals with speech impairment and enabling com-          compared to baseline [5]. (3) We introduce chaos-inspired LER\n                                         munication in acoustically challenging environments [2]. Elec-        and MSDFA losses with “modified Samba-based SSMs”, en-\n                                         tromyography (EMG) is an effective modality for recording ar-         abling a 40.79% reduction in total parameter count with signif-\n                                         ticulatory muscle activity for SSI speech production [1, 3].          icantly improved performance on the Gaddy dataset [4], sup-\n                                              EMG as a chaotic dynamical system: Articulatory EMG              porting that chaotic supervision yields better performance with\n                                      